<hl>
<seg id=1> Thailand Financial Minister Talin Visits Japan to Discuss Recovery Fund </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP, Bangkok) Thailand Financial Minister Talin left for Tokyo yesterday to discuss the Thailand portion of the US$30 billion (about S$48.6 billion) aid package provided by Japan to prevent the economies of Asian countries from slipping into a financial crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He said that he would discuss the matter in-depth during his 4 day visit to Japan, but he can't predict how much money Japan would promise to give Thailand. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Talin told the reporters at the Bangkok airport,"I had reported the loan stipulations to Premier Chuan Lee Pai last night, but we had not determined the amount, because Japan had not yet informed us." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> He said that he hoped to gain low interest and generous amortizing terms from the plan. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> He said that he would hold a meeting with Japan's Trade and Industry Ministry separately to discuss new aid to support the renewal of Thailand's industries and agriculture. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Kiichi Miyazawa, Japanese Finance Minister, announced a US$30 billion aid package at the G-7 group meeting on October 3rd. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In the short term, Japan would allocate US$15 billion to assist sectors such as trade and investment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Japan would provide direct financial aid in the form of loans from Japan Import & Export Bank and the purchase of Asian public bonds, in addition to supplying a Japanese Yen loan to Asian countries. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> It would assure loans to banks of Asian countries and issue Asian bonds to assist them in raising the wind internationally. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> The recovery aid of Kiichi Miyazawa means a lot to Thailand, because Thailand extended the plan of issuing US$500 million in international bonds last month. </seg>
<seg id=12> Thailand aimed to make use of this sum of money to inject more cash flow into economy. </seg>
<seg id=13> Thailand economy was deeply impacted by high loan costs and international new market storm. </seg>
</p>
